The paper deals with topics related to computational geometry (cs.CG) such as Lipschitz extensions and dimension reduction, as well as topics related to data structures (cs.DS) and information theory (cs.IT) such as embeddings and distortion. The use of bi-Lipschitz extensions also suggests a possible connection to numerical analysis (cs.NA). Finally, the applications of the results to prioritized and terminal dimension reduction problems suggest a possible connection to machine learning and signal processing (cs.SI).
